<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/765"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_765_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=d1e1a59988435f6e47c2ea7b6dc2a4a2&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Professor Wendy Hall" title="Professor Wendy Hall" border="0" width="120" height="88" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/765">Professor Wendy Hall appointed to European Scientific Council</a></h3><p>Professor Wendy Hall, Head of ECS, was today named by the European Commission as one of the 22 eminent founding members of the new Scientific Council of the European Research Council (ERC). The European Research Council is a new funding organization for frontier research across Europe, including science and technology, social sciences, and the humanities, which will be part of the Seventh Research Framework Programme (2007-13).</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/764"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_764_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=2284dd576e2400aa4221ca7739b0c33d&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="The Whiteley pupils at Chawton" title="The Whiteley pupils at Chawton (Copyright: David De Roure)" border="0" width="90" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/764">Creating the 'outdoor classroom'</a></h3><p>New technology from the School of Electronics and Computer Science has been trialled by pupils from the south of England. Using the latest handheld gadgets they brought history to life in stories they wrote in the grounds of Chawton House, the Elizabethan manor house that once belonged to Jane Austen's brother, Edward. Jane lived on the Chawton estate from 1809 to 1817, her most prolific writing period. A group of Year 5 students from Whiteley Primary School in Hampshire used the new technology in a unique initiative which is part of the Equator Interdisciplinary Research Collaboration.</p><p></p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/762"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_762_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=c7d7fe3071ba816e4ee076801acede82&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="120" height="91" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/762">Scientist highlights need for clearer biometrics</a></h3><p>An ECS scientist has just identified ears as a potential biometric identifier but the fact that they can be concealed by hair means further research is needed. Professor Mark Nixon, one of the UK's earliest researchers in this field, has just published a paper entitled 'Force field feature extraction for ear biometrics' in the publication Computer Vision and Image Understanding, in which he presents the case for the use of ears as a biometric.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/759"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_759_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=22a9cf398cf131f05474735d69f87d65&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Professor Wendy Hall" title="Professor Wendy Hall" border="0" width="120" height="78" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/759">Professor Wendy Hall elected new Senior VP of national Academy</a></h3><p>Professor Wendy Hall has become the first female Senior Vice President of the Royal Academy of Engineering and plans to work with the Academy to attract more women to the discipline. According to Professor Hall, Head of the School of Electronics and Computer Science (ECS) at the University of Southampton, who was elected at the AGM of the Academy on Wednesday 6 July, there is a pressing need for more women engineers--not only to achieve a more healthy gender balance in the industry but because society needs their input in design so that products can be used satisfactorily by both sexes.</p><p></p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050730084500/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
